import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Filter the data to include only the matches played by CSK
csk_data = ipl_data[(ipl_data['batting_team'] == 'Chennai Super Kings') | (ipl_data['bowling_team'] == 'Chennai Super Kings')]

# Group the filtered data by player and calculate their total runs scored
csk_runs = csk_data.groupby('batsman')['batsman_runs'].sum().reset_index()

# Sort the grouped data based on total runs scored
csk_runs_sorted = csk_runs.sort_values(by='batsman_runs', ascending=False)

# Select the top 5 performers based on total runs scored
top_5_batsmen = csk_runs_sorted.head(5)

# Create a horizontal bar chart of the top 5 performers based on total runs scored
plt.barh(top_5_batsmen['batsman'], top_5_batsmen['batsman_runs'])
plt.xlabel('Total Runs Scored')
plt.ylabel('Batsman')
plt.title('Top 5 Performers of CSK based on Total Runs Scored')
plt.show()

# filter the data to only include powerplay overs
powerplay_data = ipl_data[ipl_data['over'] <= 6]

# group the data by batsman and sum the runs and balls faced
batsman_runs = powerplay_data.groupby('batsman')['batsman_runs'].sum()
balls_faced = powerplay_data.groupby('batsman')['ball'].count()

# calculate the strike rate for each batsman
strike_rates = (batsman_runs / balls_faced) * 100

# sort the batsmen by their strike rate in descending order
top_batsmen = strike_rates.sort_values(ascending=False).head(5)

In [33]:
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
from scipy.stats.mstats import winsorize

# filter the data to include only powerplay overs
powerplay_data = ipl_data[ipl_data['over'] <= 6]

# calculate the total runs scored by each batsman in the powerplay
batsman_runs = powerplay_data.groupby('batsman')['total_runs'].sum().reset_index()

# select the top 5 batsmen by runs scored
top_batsmen = batsman_runs.nlargest(5, 'total_runs')['batsman'].tolist()

# filter the data to include only data for the top 5 batsmen
top_batsmen_data = powerplay_data[powerplay_data['batsman'].isin(top_batsmen)]

# winsorize the runs scored data
winsorized_runs = winsorize(top_batsmen_data['total_runs'], (0.01, 0.01))

# create a new dataframe with the winsorized data
top_batsmen_data_winsorized = top_batsmen_data.copy()
top_batsmen_data_winsorized['winsorized_runs'] = winsorized_runs

# create the boxplot using seaborn
sns.boxplot(x='batsman', y='winsorized_runs', data=top_batsmen_data_winsorized, showfliers=False)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the data
df = pd.read_csv(path)

# Filter for Rohit Sharma and Virat Kohli
rohit = df[df['batsman'] == 'RG Sharma']
kohli = df[df['batsman'] == 'V Kohli']

# Group the data by inning and calculate the total runs for each batsman
rohit_runs = rohit.groupby(['inning'])['batsman_runs'].sum().reset_index()
kohli_runs = kohli.groupby(['inning'])['batsman_runs'].sum().reset_index()

# Merge the data for both batsmen
stats = pd.merge(rohit_runs, kohli_runs, on='inning', suffixes=('_Rohit', '_Kohli'))

# Create a bar plot to compare the runs scored by each batsman in different innings
stats.plot(x='inning', y=['batsman_runs_Rohit', 'batsman_runs_Kohli'], kind='bar')
plt.title('Comparison of Runs Scored by Rohit Sharma and Virat Kohli')
plt.xlabel('Inning')
plt.ylabel('Runs Scored')
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv(path)

# Filter for Virat Kohli's innings during overs 7-15
kohli_df = df[(df['batsman'] == 'V Kohli') & (df['over'] >= 7) & (df['over'] <= 15)]

# Group by match and calculate total runs scored in the middle overs
kohli_runs = kohli_df.groupby(['id', 'inning'])['batsman_runs'].sum().reset_index()

# Create scatter plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(kohli_runs['id'], kohli_runs['batsman_runs'], s=50)
plt.xlabel('Match ID')

plt.title('Virat Kohli Performance in Middle Overs')

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# load the dataset
df = pd.read_csv(path)

# filter for the last 5 overs
df_last_5_overs = df[df['over'] >= 16]

# group by batsman and sum the runs
runs_by_batsman = df_last_5_overs.groupby('batsman')['batsman_runs'].sum()

# sort the values in descending order and select top 10 batsmen
top_10_batsmen = runs_by_batsman.sort_values(ascending=False).head(10)

# create a bar chart
plt.bar(top_10_batsmen.index, top_10_batsmen.values)

# add title and labels
plt.title('Top 10 Batsmen by Runs in Last 5 Overs')
plt.xlabel('Batsman')
plt.ylabel('Runs')

# rotate x-axis labels for better readability
plt.xticks(rotation=90)

# display the chart
plt.show()

import pandas as pd

# Read in the data
data = pd.read_csv(path)

# Filter the data for overs 16-20
last_overs_data = data[data['over'] >= 16]

# Group the data by bowler and calculate the total runs conceded and total balls bowled
bowler_stats = last_overs_data.groupby('bowler').agg({'batsman_runs': 'sum', 'ball': 'count'})

# Calculate the economy rate for each bowler
bowler_stats['economy_rate'] = bowler_stats['batsman_runs'] / (bowler_stats['ball'] / 6)

# Sort the data by economy rate
best_economy = bowler_stats.sort_values('economy_rate').head(10)

# Create a bar chart to visualize the data
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.bar(best_economy.index, best_economy['economy_rate'])
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.xlabel('Bowler')
plt.ylabel('Economy Rate')
plt.title('Best economy bowlers in last overs')
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# read the dataset
df = pd.read_csv(path)

# filter for last 5 overs
df_last_overs = df[df['over'] >= 15]

# group by bowler and calculate the economy rate
economy_rates = df_last_overs.groupby('bowler')['total_runs'].sum() / (df_last_overs.groupby('bowler').size() / 6)

# exclude outliers with less than 5 overs bowled
bowlers_5plus_overs = economy_rates[df_last_overs.groupby('bowler').size() >= 30]

# sort by economy rate and get top 5 bowlers
top_5_bowlers = bowlers_5plus_overs.sort_values().head(5)

# plot the bar chart
plt.bar(top_5_bowlers.index, top_5_bowlers.values)
plt.title('Top 5 Bowlers in Last 5 Overs by Economy Rate (minimum 5 overs)')
plt.xlabel('Bowler')
plt.ylabel('Economy Rate')
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the data
df = pd.read_csv(path)

# Filter for last 3 overs
last_3_overs = df[df['over'] > 17]

# Groupby bowler and count wickets
wickets = last_3_overs.groupby('bowler')['is_wicket'].sum().reset_index()

# Filter for bowlers with at least 5 overs bowled
min_overs = 5
bowlers = last_3_overs.groupby('bowler').filter(lambda x: x['over'].count() >= min_overs)
wickets = bowlers.groupby('bowler')['is_wicket'].sum().reset_index()

# Sort by wickets and take top 5
top_5_wicket_takers = wickets.sort_values('is_wicket', ascending=False).head(5)

# Create bar chart of wickets taken
plt.bar(top_5_wicket_takers['bowler'], top_5_wicket_takers['is_wicket'])
plt.xlabel('Bowler')
plt.ylabel('Wickets Taken')
plt.title('Most Wicket-Taking Bowlers in Last 3 Overs')
plt.show()
